Text.Value: Say I decide to try this Underdark route after all - how do I get started?
Now, we've quite the journey ahead. Best get started.
Are these Sharrans still to be found?
We get a cure and the chance to hit these arseholes where they live? Sounds good to me.
Perhaps... but I wouldn't want to place all my faith in blind luck.
I had no idea anyone beyond their ranks was infected. You have my sincere sympathies.
There's also the shadow curse - it's an affront and must be cleansed.
I don't know what you're talking about.
I am Halsin, First Druid of the Emerald Grove - and I owe you my thanks.
One of those who died had a clue that was supposed to help us find the hidden entrance to the Underdark.
These tadpoles obey one master. If the ghaik have united in a single Creed, my Queen is in danger.
And where do you suppose that ship was taking you? Moonrise, I'll wager. The journey differs, but the problem is the same.
Dark Justiciars? I must see for myself.
Sympathies? Can't you help me?
How do you know all this?
You could also go under. There is a tunnel somewhere in the ruined temple of Selûne. It leads to Moonrise Towers through the Underdark.
I'm glad you approve - I do not truly care if you approve, but I am glad.
There is a tunnel leading from the temple of Selûne right down into the Underdark and beyond. The entrance is hidden somewhere in the ruins.
I'll trust your judgement.
I will join you, help you with that which plagues you. The illithid curse is a blight to all nature.
I'm shielded from the worst of the parasite's magic.
Couldn't Nettie take over?
I'd still be target practice for goblins if you hadn't come along. I think I can trust you.
No, this is different. Altered. But I believe I know where answers can be found - Moonrise Towers.
If you hadn't killed the leaders of that goblin horde, the grove would be no more. I am in your debt.
There's a chokehold of magic, binding the creature to you. Any efforts to remove it would almost certainly kill you - or worse.
It's lost to me. Perhaps in time I can open it up to the world again, but for now, I must help you.
You're welcome, I suppose.
I was expecting more from you than a lead towards some distant, dangerous prospect.
Few survive long - those who do are transformed by the curse. It is not a place to venture into lightly.
I found the hidden entrance in the temple of Selûne - the way is clear.
The path is now clear - we have to get to Moonrise Towers. Do you remember what I told you? About getting there?
I found an elevator - but it leads right into the shadow curse.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: This node if the player clicked the elevator from Grymforge to SCL

Text.Value: Tread carefully. You're on the right track, I'm sure - but there'll still be danger and difficulty before you reach Moonrise.
Indeed, and may the Oak Father watch over us on our journey. We will speak soon, I'm sure.
She can tend to the grove, help it heal. In time, others will join. Perhaps some day I can return.
Seems it's high time we got on our way.
But in my eagerness, I put far too much faith in the abilities of Aradin and his band. We didn't even get close.
All too well - I could even sense it from afar. Now let me confirm it; I need to know exactly what we're dealing with...
It's the source of this magic, and where the cultists send their captives - to be infected. They're building an army. Innocents go in, True Souls come out.
I know. It's what brings me here.
What, were you expecting a spell? A potion? Or perhaps you thought I'd conduct a cack-handed operation on you right here.
This shadow curse - does it affect Shar worshippers?
You mentioned you had unfinished business in Moonrise Towers - what did you mean?
I know - your infection.
At last, a cure is in reach. To the Towers, then, where the moonlight will lend way to a new dawn.
A drow forced me to defend myself. Afterwards, I was able to study the parasite that slithered out of the corpse, see what drives these 'True Souls'.
I would like to join your camp, if you'll allow me. I can offer my skills, my counsel.
But... something's different. You're aware of the monster inside you. You don't bow to the Absolute, like the True Souls do...
I'm not entirely sure - but I'll take all the help I can get.
The decision is yours, but I'd favour the Underdark. Even a place like that is the lesser evil compared to the shadow-cursed lands.
What about the grove?
Keep looking. If they're present, then it's likely there's a route to Moonrise somewhere.
I advise you start in the temple of Selûne - if you find the Dark Justiciars' hidden entrance, it could lead you all the way to Moonrise.
I need her to stay focused on her training - the grove will need a skilled healer in my absence.
So it seems, though I don't know how. You will have to choose your approach carefully.
Sounds rather ingenious.
Very shrewd of you.
Moonrise Towers? What is that place?
The Absolute's forces can tolerate such a place?
First and only Druid. What will Francesca even do here?
But I'm afraid it won't be easy, or quick.
And I may be able to help you find a more definitive solution to your problem.
Don't worry, I'm not here just to sing your praises. I believe I can help - with your tadpole.
This magic you mentioned - it isn't normal for these parasites?
Nature speaks to me. Birds report what they've seen. And I've overheard goblins speaking of it, too. Moonrise is at the heart of all this, I'm sure of it.
You learned all this from your studies?
I'm certain. The Underdark is dangerous, yes, but the alternative is suicide. Be patient and be thorough - the path will reveal itself in time.
I already found the place you're talking about - it's called Grymforge.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: This QN if the player has already entered the grymforge but has not yet spoken to Halsin about it.

Text.Value: I wish to come with you, help solve this problem that's plaguing you. It's the least I can do.
Indeed. We've quite the journey ahead of us.
You learned all this from your studies?
This magic you mentioned - it isn't normal for these parasites?
I heard how you saved the grove; it wouldn't be right for me to let you leave without expressing my gratitude.
As bones, perhaps. But their hidden structures might still remain.
You could go overland - along the Risen Road or through the mountains. Easier at first, but you'll run into the shadow curse eventually.
What about the grove?
I've chosen a successor as First Druid - Francesca of the High Forest. A bird's already been dispatched to summon her.
How do you know all this?
I never thought I'd say this, but it sounds like the Underdark is the safer route.
Few can resist it without dying or transforming into shadow beings. You can try to journey overland if you wish, but I strongly advise you go under.
I believe if you find this entrance, you'll discover a route that leads to Moonrise Towers, bypassing the worst of the shadow curse.
Be glad it did, or you'd be a True Soul by now.
My thanks again, for all you did. With the grove safe, I am free to turn to other matters.
This magic isn't typical of ceremorphosis?
Thank you. I will grieve when I can, but for now, I must find another way to serve nature - by helping you.
By all means - pursue any leads you may have. But I sense all roads will lead to Moonrise, in the end.
The Underdark's my home. Better to take that route than risk this curse.
Don't be coy - I can sense the imbalance in you. Now let me confirm it, so I can be certain of what we're dealing with...
Once we are cleansed, we infiltrate Moonrise Towers. Should there be ghaik, we snatch their heads, one by one.
How is this possible...?
I suppose it was too much to hope we were going to be cured here and now. To Moonrise, then.
Long ago, a man called Ketheric Thorm built a secret stronghold deep down there, before rallying a whole army of Dark Justiciars - Shar worshippers.
Remind me.
A fellow druid. I can count on her to tend to the grove in my absence. Help it heal.
What about one of the others? Rath, perhaps?
I wasn't taken to Moonrise - I was infected on a mind flayer ship, before it crashed.
You may reconsider once you see the effects of the curse for yourself.
It is sealed off to me, to the whole world. Forever, perhaps.
'Almost'? That means I still have a chance. One I intend to take.
An ancient citadel, abandoned for years - and for very good reason - until these cultists took it over.
I sensed what was done to you from afar. Now let me confirm it; I need to know exactly what we're dealing with...
A drow forced me to defend myself. Afterwards, I was able to study the parasite that slithered out of the corpse, see what drives these 'True Souls'.
I had no idea anyone beyond their ranks was infected. You have my sincere sympathies.
That must be where the ship was taking me - before it crashed.
There is a terrible curse surrounding Moonrise Towers - a shadow curse that drains away all light and life.
I helped overthrow Ketheric Thorm and his Dark Justiciars years ago. But I failed to prevent him from unleashing darkness across the region before he was defeated.
That sounds... novel. What is it that protects you?
Or I was, at least. I went there - the grove is sealed off to me, to the whole world.
Sounds like the grove will be in good hands, then. We should get going.
Forget about the grove. What are you doing here?
Luckily, you have time - this magic has slowed your ceremorphosis to a crawl. I just can't fathom why someone would do that.
This is why I chose Francesca. She will restore simplicity and purity to the grove in my absence.
Anything is preferable to risking the shadow curse.
Sympathies? Can't you help me?
I've long sought to return to Moonrise Towers - unfinished business. It seems our fates have aligned.
You're half right - you have to get to Moonrise, but you still have a choice of how to get there.
Won't this cause resentment?
The grove needs to move beyond the mistakes of the past. What it needs is an unknown quantity; an outsider who can enforce the Oak Father's teachings without bias.
Doesn't sound like I've much choice - I need to get to Moonrise, curse or not.
How are you so sure Moonrise is where I have to go?
This is sobering news indeed, but there's no use crying over spilt milk. If this is our only option, to Moonrise Towers we go.
Precisely. If we can understand just what this magic is, then perhaps we can rid you of this parasite.
There's a chokehold of magic, binding the creature to you. Any efforts to remove it would almost certainly kill you - or worse.
I escaped from an illithid ship after being infected. Maybe the process was interrupted.
I spent years researching the curse, trying to put an end to it. Nothing has worked - yet.
Resentment will spring up like mushrooms no matter what I do. You cannot please everyone and you'd be a fool to try.
You'll need to pick up where Aradin left off - find the hidden entrance. It's somewhere in the temple of Selûne.
What do you suggest?
I have nowhere else to turn, it seems. I went to the grove, but... I cannot face what has happened there.
If we can get to Moonrise and understand just what this magic is, then perhaps we can rid you of this parasite.
Aradin and his lot were looking for a way down there - they were promised riches if they retrieved a relic called the Nightsong. But I think there's more.
I know the Underdark - it's lethal. I'll travel overland.
A dwarf called Brian, I believe. Though there's no guarantee that the goblins left him recognisable.
So how do I find this underground route?
I was right to seek you out. You're after a cure for this parasite.
A fine camp you have here. Certainly an improvement on that filthy cage the goblins had me in.

EditorData.logicalname: Said he would join at camp.

Text.Value: It's immensely powerful, whatever it is - strong enough to slow ceremorphosis to a crawl. Luckily, that gives you more time.
I am Halsin, First Druid of the Emerald Grove.
There is hope... but it isn't found here, at my hands - at least not yet.
Patience. I can't just snap my fingers... but I know where the solution almost certainly lies - Moonrise Towers.
I may be able to help you find a more definitive solution to your problem.
And you think I'll find a cure if I find this source at Moonrise?
Your resolve is most admirable. It'll serve you well for where you've to go - Moonrise Towers.
Patience. I can't just snap my fingers... but I know where the solution almost certainly lies - Moonrise Towers.
I owe you a debt for seeing to the goblins' leaders. Now I'm here to pay that debt.
Those illithid creatures threaten the natural order - it's my duty to do what I can to stop them.
What about the grove?
Absolute followers - but that's about all.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: This node if the player didn't click the elevator from Grymforge to SCL

Text.Value: From this stronghold, Ketheric's forces could access both the temple of Selûne and Moonrise Towers - but he was defeated before he could launch an attack.
There must be other ways to cure myself - my kin have dealt with these parasites before.
I'm sure there must be other ways to cure myself.
Is that why you went with Aradin? You thought he might find this route to Moonrise?
I don't know.
Who?
Already...? If only I'd gone with you instead of Aradin.
Indeed. After we dealt with the drow that ambushed us, Nettie and I were able to inspect the corpse - and the creature that slithered out of it.
Precisely! Who indeed? You do not know, and neither do any of the others.

EditorData.NodeContext: Turning the player's question back on them - they've inadvertently stumbled upon the reasoning behind his decision

Text.Value: Contrary to how some think of us, we druids can play politics when necessary.
If you can find this place, I'll wager it will reveal a path to Moonrise Towers, bypassing the worst of the shadow curse.
I won't be held accountable just because you're naive enough to expect easy answers. Now allow me to continue.
Let's go, then.
What's so dangerous?
Rath has promise, but he has a ways to go yet. He wasn't able to stop Kagha by himself. The grove needs experience and a strong hand.
Oak Father preserve you, child... You're infected, aren't you? The mind flayers' spawn.
Aradin and his lot were looking for the same entrance - they sought an artefact called the Nightsong that was supposed to be housed somewhere down there.
I've got more exploring to do.
Finally, we're catching up on our puppet master. And the hunt ends at Moonrise Towers.
Precisely. Then perhaps I could have done something about both the shadow curse and ceremorphosis aberrations.
One of the adventurers had a clue to help find it - a dwarf called Brian. It might still be found on his corpse, wherever the goblins left it.
I don't know. Ketheric's followers were defeated or vanished before the effects of the curse took hold.
I am Halsin, First Druid of the Emerald Grove - which you saved. Thank you.
No. At least, not right now.
What would you do?
This magic isn't typical of ceremorphosis?
I remember. To Moonrise Towers, then.
How do I find this passage through the Underdark?
That sounds like what you need. But the next part of the journey mightn't be straightforward - or safe.
No, this is different. Altered. But I believe I know where answers can be found - Moonrise Towers.
Hmm. Sometimes a mysterious cure is worse than the disease.
I don't want to risk getting lost in the Underdark - I'll journey overland.
That's it? Just go to this place?
It may prove impossible to avoid the shadow curse entirely, but if you find any way to limit your exposure, seize it.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: GLO_Halsin_AcknowledgedGrymforge sets whenever the player enquires about the Grymforge and Halsin acknowledges how it may relate to the journey to Moonrise.

Text.Value: May Silvanus guide us.
That doesn't sound much like hope to me. Can't you help?
A fine camp you have here. My apologies for showing up unannounced.
You promised you'd do something about my infection.
Apart from facing legions of Absolute followers? The whole region is shrouded in a curse - a shadow curse.
I'm sorry about the grove.
First Druid? You sound like someone who could help with a problem I have...
Looking for you, of course. We have work to do.
That place is where the cultists send their captives. Innocents go in, True Souls come out. It has to be the source of this magic.
Indeed. After we dealt with the drow that ambushed us, Nettie and I were able to inspect the corpse - and the creature that slithered out of it.
There's no time to spare, then - to Moonrise Towers.
You can see that I have free will - you don't need to know any more than that.
What were you expecting? That I'd mumble a spell or whip out a potion?

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Halsin raises a hand to your head, magically connecting with you (no contact). He gives an alarmed look - he knows what’s inside you

Text.Value: I'm here for you. I believe I can help with the parasite lurking within.
If I can join you and get close to Moonrise, perhaps I can lift this curse, same as you may find a cure for your infection.
You want to go to Moonrise yourself? Why?
You know about my problem...?
There's nobody in the grove you'd choose?
That doesn't sound much like hope to me. Can't you just help here and now?
For years now, this curse has consumed all light and life. It spits out only darkness and despair.
You've already been? Impressive. You'll make me redundant at this rate. What did you find?

EditorData.NodeContext: Impressed and a little amused at the player's diligence (finding a place before he can even tell them about it)

Text.Value: Find whoever's behind the parasites and the magic. If we can understand it, then perhaps we can cure it - provided you survive long enough.
Danger. Are you sure that's the best way to Moonrise?
Wait, please. There's more. The whole region around Moonrise is shrouded in a curse - a shadow curse.
I've already found a way into the Underdark. I can pick up the trail from there.

Synopsis:
The druid Halsin appears at the player's camp and offers to help them find a cure for their tadpoles - a journey that will take them to a dangerous new region.
(This dialog will play as a fallback Halsin is intended to join the player's camp in the event of a Grove lockdown or  if the player murders the grove/attack on den is auto-completed.)
